Yep — **if you put the Note X10 in “Pen Tablet Mode” and connect it to your computer**, your JavaScript `<canvas>` will see it like a normal pen/mouse. You can draw with it and even read **pressure (and tilt) via Pointer Events** in modern browsers.

What you need
- Swap the paper for the plastic panel, install the Huion driver, then connect by USB-C or Bluetooth. That turns it into a standard graphics tablet (8192 pressure, ±60° tilt). citeturn0search5turn0search22  
- Browsers expose stylus data through **Pointer Events** (`pointerdown/move/up`) with `event.pressure` (0–1), `tiltX`, `tiltY`, etc. (Chrome/Edge/Safari: good; Firefox can be finicky). citeturn0search6turn0search2turn0search14turn0search18  
- On Windows, if pressure doesn’t show up, enable **Windows Ink** in the Huion driver. (Some apps need it; same trick often helps the browser.) citeturn0search7turn0search11  
- Note: On **Linux**, the X10’s pen-tablet mode is **wired only** (Bluetooth not supported). citeturn0search9  
- Also note: the X10 is **not a touchscreen**; it controls the cursor on your monitor, not on the X10 itself. citeturn0search22

Tiny pressure-aware canvas starter
```html
<canvas id="c" width="900" height="600" style="border:1px solid #ccc"></canvas>
<script>
const canvas = document.getElementById('c');
const ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
let drawing = false;

canvas.addEventListener('pointerdown', e => {
  canvas.setPointerCapture(e.pointerId);
  drawing = true;
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.moveTo(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
});

canvas.addEventListener('pointermove', e => {
  if (!drawing) return;
  // pressure is 0..1; fall back to a thin line for mice
  const p = e.pressure > 0 ? e.pressure : 0.2;
  ctx.lineWidth = 1 + p * 9;           // 1–10 px
  ctx.lineCap = 'round';
  ctx.lineTo(e.offsetX, e.offsetY);
  ctx.stroke();
});

canvas.addEventListener('pointerup', () => (drawing = false));
</script>
```

If you run that in Chrome/Edge/Safari on your Mac/PC with the Note X10 in Pen Tablet Mode, you should get variable-width strokes with pressure. If you need tilt, read `e.tiltX`/`e.tiltY` the same way. citeturn0search6

If you were hoping to do this **on an iPad/phone**, the X10 won’t act as a stylus there — it only syncs notes to the Huion app on mobile. For in-browser canvas on mobile, you’d use the device’s own stylus (e.g., Apple Pencil). citeturn0search22
